**Pear shaped diamond earrings** achieve something no other earring shape can: a recognizable, high-fashion teardrop silhouette that reads immediately from across a room. The elongated brilliant cut delivers 8–12% more face-up surface area than a round diamond of identical weight, which means every dollar of carat spends further in earring form than in any other jewelry category. This guide covers every pear diamond earring at Blue Nile — prong studs, bezel studs, halo studs, drop earrings, huggie hoops, and statement pieces — across every metal and carat range, from entry-level **pear diamond studs** at $438 to extraordinary natural diamond drops at $14,430, all with {{month}} {{year}} prices and affiliate links.

Whether you are shopping for **pear shaped diamond stud earrings** as an everyday staple, **1 carat pear shaped diamond earrings** as a milestone gift, **pear diamond earrings in yellow gold** for a warm fashion-forward look, **pear shaped diamond earrings in white gold** for a classic bridal-adjacent finish, or **pear shaped lab grown diamond earrings** to maximize carat size at a given budget, every option is catalogued below with the current price data you need to buy with confidence.

**TL;DR:** Every pear earring listing at Blue Nile shows carat total weight — the combined weight of both stones. "1 ct tw" means 0.50 ct per ear, not 1.00 ct per ear. → If you want meaningful visible diamond at each earlobe, you need to start at 1 CTW. The [1 CTW Lab Prong Studs in 14K White Gold at $828](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/pear-cut-lab-grown-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-f-g-vs2-si1-item-251889?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — currently 40% off — are the single most over-delivered value in this entire guide. For bezel protection with natural stones, [Bezel Natural 0.5 CTW White Gold at $1,650](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/bezel-diamond-stud-earrings-with-05-ctw-pear-shaped-diamonds-in-14k-white-gold-item-297319?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the correct entry point. Every other decision — metal, setting style, drop vs. stud — is secondary to understanding CTW first.

---

## The CTW Trap

The most common and most costly misunderstanding in pear diamond earring shopping: **CTW means carat total weight, split between both ears.** Not per ear. Both ears combined.

A buyer searching for **"1 carat pear shaped diamond earrings"** expects to receive 1.00 ct of diamond per ear — two impressive teardrop solitaires. What they receive, if they buy a "1 ct tw" listing without reading closely, is 0.50 ct per ear. That is still a beautiful, noticeable stone. But it is not what most people visualize when they read "1 carat."

Here is the complete math:

| What the listing says | Stone per ear | What you actually get |
|---|---|---|
| 1/4 CTW | 0.125 ct | Delicate accent pear |
| 1/2 CTW | 0.25 ct | Small, discreet teardrop |
| 1 CTW | 0.50 ct | Clearly visible, everyday-appropriate |
| 2 CTW | 1.00 ct | Statement-level per ear |
| 3 CTW | 1.50 ct | Bold, high-fashion |
| 4 CTW | 2.00 ct | Red-carpet tier |

The CTW trap catches buyers at every budget level. Someone spending $5,750 on a [1 CTW Natural Prong Stud in White Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/pear-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is buying 0.50 ct per ear — which is lovely — but a buyer expecting 1 ct per ear at that price would be deeply disappointed. Set your per-ear size goal first, then multiply by two to find your CTW target. This single adjustment corrects the most common earring-buying mistake.

---

## The Orientation Rule

Pear diamonds have a point at one end and a rounded belly at the other. In a matched pair of earrings, both stones must be oriented the same way — and that orientation affects how the earrings read on the ear.

**Point up (classic):** The tip of the pear faces toward the top of the ear. The rounded end sits at the bottom. This creates the classic teardrop silhouette — wide at the base, tapering upward — that reads as a dewdrop clinging to the earlobe. Blue Nile's prong stud series and bezel stud series are pre-matched point-up pairs. This is the correct orientation for studs worn as a primary statement piece.

**Point down (pendant-style):** The rounded belly faces upward, the tip hangs down. This mimics the natural drop of a pendant and is preferred in dangling earrings, where the pear swings freely and the point hangs toward the jawline.

**Why this matters:** When buyers source individual pear diamonds from a build-your-own setting, the backing hardware — the post — is attached at a fixed rotation. A poorly matched pair of pear studs where one stone points up and one is rotated slightly will look uneven from the front. Buying pre-matched pairs from a reputable retailer eliminates this problem entirely. All Blue Nile pear stud earrings are pre-matched and oriented correctly at manufacture.

For **pear shaped yellow diamond earrings** or fancy-color pears sourced individually, verify with the retailer that both stones are graded from the same parcel and are matched in orientation before the posts are set.

